info.description:
Azure DevOps REST API
=====================

[Primary documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/azure/devops/)

OpenAPI and Swagger
-------------------

Find these on GitHub: https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/vsts-rest-api-specs

Collections and Environments
----------------------------

The Collection Variables contain a collection of values that are used by the requests to assemble URLs, requests, and identify properties of request or response objects, regardless of which Azure DevOps Service or Azure DevOps Server (or Team Foundation Server) is being targeted.

Use an Environment to provide specific values that apply for one specific Azure DevOps Service organization or Azure DevOps Server collection. Import Azure DevOps Environment templates to populate the Environment with possible variable names. Once imported, change the values of variables accordingly.

ALERT: Some variables can store sensitive information, like Personal Access Tokens or client secrets. ***DO NOT STORE THESE VALUES IN THE "INITIAL VALUE" COLUMN. ONLY STORE SENSITIVE VALUES IN THE "CURRENT VALUE" COLUMN.***

The Collection uses a combination of Collection variables and Environment variables to formulate the requests and process them. Generally, set values in the Environment, not in the Collection. Use the Collection variables as part of the formulas to set the Environment variables.

Authorization
=============

Choose authorization using the Collection's Authorization tab.

To use a Personal Access Token (PAT):

1. Set the Authorization method to **Basic Auth**

2. Clear the **Username** field and leave it blank.

3. Set the **Password** field to the literal value (including the double curly-braces):

    {{Ads:PersonalAccessToken}}

4. Close the Collection settings editor, and open the Environment you want to use for the targeted Azure DevOps instance. Suggested naming convention (choose the appropriate depth as needed):

    AzureDevOps â–¶ {organization}/{project}/{team} 

5. Find or create the variable named `{{Ads:PersonalAccessToken}}`. Set the value to the exact value copied from Azure DevOps. ONLY use the **Current** value, *never* the Initial value, in order to prevent the value from being shared outside your local work area.
